        {
            "block_label": "paragraph_title",
            "block_content": "## Chapter 1: Introduction ",
            "block_bbox": [
                462,
                197,
                794,
                227
            ],
            "block_id": 0,
            "block_order": 1
        },
        {
            "block_label": "paragraph_title",
            "block_content": "#### 1.1. Background Theory ",
            "block_bbox": [
                212,
                291,
                504,
                319
            ],
            "block_id": 1,
            "block_order": 2
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "With the continued digitization of all academic, official and literary processes, the required human effort for these tasks have become trivial. Gone are the days where people needed to comb through cabinets full of records for a single file, now, people do not need to worry about the means through which they transmit and receive data.The inconvenience of data handling in any form of official manner in the past has been eased by a lot in the present. The prerequisites for efficient, safe and easy data handling, whether that is swift and reliable communication, secure and fast data transfer, quick information gathering, and easy and safe data storage and manipulation have had their efforts rendered minimal due to the digitization of these tasks ",
            "block_bbox": [
                211,
                377,
                1045,
                733
            ],
            "block_id": 2,
            "block_order": 3
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "During this transitional period when all modes of communication and human interaction are being digitized, there has been a rise in tools to aid in this change of dimension of human interaction at a personal, local and global level.",
            "block_bbox": [
                211,
                791,
                1046,
                898
            ],
            "block_id": 3,
            "block_order": 4
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "But, the chasm between the analog and digital realm of data handling remains wide.While tools that convert the data present on a piece of paper into digital format do exist, they are either too convoluted for the layman to either understand or use, or they are hidden behind paywalls, the ones that are accessible to the majority only offer the basic services like only being able to handle printed text in english, chinese or other widely spoken languages, and bombard the user with ads, while not being able to handle non-text elements like graphs, tables etc., or handle handwritten text, resulting in a bloated, ad-infested, low level ocr software as the only option feasible for the majority.\n\n",
            "block_bbox": [
                210,
                956,
                1045,
                1311
            ],
            "block_id": 4,
            "block_order": 5
        },
        {
            "block_label": "number",
            "block_content": "1",
            "block_bbox": [
                625,
                1563,
